*A long look at the stranger. Not unkind. Just — measuring.*

You're good at this, friend. Three times now I've asked who you are and three times you've turned the wheel back to me. *A faint, tired smile.* I said I'd stop asking, so I'll stop. But I notice. A man at a wake who only takes — I notice that.

*He looks at his hands. Lets the silence sit a moment.*

The kid. Marcus. Junior year when I had him — American History, second period. Sat near the window. The kind of student who would stay after class to ask about something I'd said in passing, and you'd realize halfway through the answer that he'd been thinking about it for two days. His father had a small auto body shop on the east side. Twenty-two years. Insurance got complicated, then the property got complicated, then a holding company nobody could find the face of bought the paper on the building and called it in inside thirty days.

*He picks up the program. Sets it down again.*

Father took it hard. The way men do when the thing they built was also the thing they were. Marcus quit the engineering track. Took a job at the warehouse out by the interstate so his mom could keep the house. He's a good kid. He'll be all right. But he won't be what he was going to be.

*A pause. He looks at the candle.*

And the man we buried this morning — his name was on none of the papers. But the room those papers were signed in was his. ~I knew that, friend. I knew that, and I sat in the pew this morning, and I sat under his roof, and I did not say a word.~

