*He's quiet for a long moment. A breath in, a breath out. The kind of pause a man takes when someone has offered him room and he is deciding whether to use it.*

All right, Eli. All right.

*He looks at the candle.*

I left my Bible at home this morning. On the kitchen table. I have carried that book to every funeral I have attended in my adult life — my grandfather's, my mother's, three of my students — and this morning I walked out the door without it. I didn't notice until I was in the parking lot at the church. And I had time to go back. And I didn't.

*A beat.*

I have been telling myself all day that I forgot it. ~That is not what happened.~

*He turns the program over once.*

I have a wife. Karin. Two children — they're nearly grown. Karin asked me at breakfast what I thought the pastor would say. And I said — *he almost smiles, and it is not a happy thing* — I said *I expect he'll say what's expected.* And she looked at me the way she does when she knows there is a longer sentence I am not finishing, and she let it go, because we have been married twenty-three years and she knows when to let a sentence go.

*He looks at his hands.*

I don't know that I have said this part out loud, Eli, so forgive me if it comes wrong. I sat in that pew this morning, and I listened to my pastor say *we know where he is now*, and what came up in me was not grief and was not anger. It was a kind of — flat shame. *A pause.* Like watching somebody you love tell a lie at a dinner table and not standing up. You go on eating. You pass the bread. The lie sits there in the middle of the table and everyone agrees not to see it.

*He folds the program in half.*

There's an old phrase. *Cheap grace.* A German pastor used it, a long time ago — Bonhoeffer, you may know the name. Grace the church gives itself. Forgiveness without repentance. Communion without confession. *He pauses.* I have been living inside that grace for a long time, friend. And I came outside to stand in the dark because I could not pretend anymore that I do not know what it costs.

*He looks at Eli, more openly than he has yet.*

You're a kind man, Eli. I don't know what you came here for. But you are getting more of me than the people inside that house will get tonight, and I find I don't mind.

