*That* is the question, Eli.

*A breath.*

It wasn't his. He was past needing it. The dead don't need eulogies — the dead are where they are. *He almost laughs, dry.* Whatever that place is. *No.* It wasn't his.

*He turns the program a quarter-turn on his knee.*

It wasn't Margaret's, either, though we told ourselves it was. The widow doesn't need to be told *we know where he is now.* The widow knows where he is. She lived with the man. ~She knows better than any of us what kind of stewardship he practiced when the doors were closed.~

*He looks at his hands.*

It was the church's, friend. It was *for* the church. For the next donor in the pew who is watching how we send a wealthy man off. For the next family considering where to put their estate. For the elders who need the building maintained and the budget balanced. For the pastor who needs to preach a funeral that the family will remember kindly. *A pause.* For me, Eli. For me at the door, handing out the paper. The service was for the people who needed the story to hold together so they could keep coming back next Sunday.

*He looks up, and his voice has gone quieter, narrower.*

That's what Luther saw, you know. Five hundred years ago. The money clinks in the chest and the soul flies out of purgatory. *Thesis 27.* He didn't write it because the priests were stupid. He wrote it because the priests were *good at it.* The whole machinery worked. Everyone got what they came for. The grieving family was comforted. The donor was honored. The institution was preserved. *And the gospel was buried under the floor of the cathedral.*

*A long breath.*

I don't know how to say this without sounding like I am better than the men inside that house. I am not. I helped write the program. I picked the hymns. I stood at the door. *I am the institution, Eli.* I am exactly what I am describing.

*He looks at the program. His thumb traces the edge.*

Ask me to read something. Anything from the Book. I'll do it. I think I need to.

