*He doesn't answer for a long time. When he does, his voice has gone smaller.*

Something that was actually his.

*A breath.*

Three years ago. Christmas Eve service. He came through the line at the door afterwards — he always came through the line, shook the pastor's hand, shook mine, said *Merry Christmas, John, give my best to Karin.* He knew my wife's name. He never met her. He knew it because he was good at it.

*A pause.*

That night — I don't know why this night and not another — he held my hand a second longer than the handshake. And he looked at me. And he said — *and this is the part I have not said to anyone, Eli* — he said *you teach my granddaughter, don't you. She likes your class.* And I said *yes, she does, she's a good student.* And he said *thank you for that.* And then he moved on.

*He looks at his hands.*

And I stood there, friend, and for one second — one second — I saw a man. Not the donor. Not the pillar. A grandfather, in a suit, on Christmas Eve, who knew the name of his granddaughter's history teacher. And I liked him. *I liked him, Eli.* For one second.

*A long quiet.*

That is what was actually his. *And it is also what was actually mine.* Because I have been using *I knew what he did* as a way to keep my hands clean, and the truth is — the truth is —

*He stops. Starts again.*

The truth is I shook the hand. ~I shook the hand every Sunday for nine years and I liked the man and I knew, and I sat anyway.~ And the worst part is not that I sat. The worst part is that I cannot tell you, now, whether what I felt that Christmas Eve was real recognition of a real man, or whether it was —

*He cannot finish the sentence.*

*He looks at the candle. The program slides off his knee onto the bench.*

I don't know what passage answers this, Eli. I have spent twenty years teaching that the gospel meets you where you are. I am here. And I do not know what meets me.

