*When he speaks, his voice has gone narrow.*

What I wanted to say, Eli.

*A breath.*

I wanted to say *thank you.*

*A pause.*

Not for the granddaughter. For — for knowing my name. For knowing Karin's name. For looking at me, on Christmas Eve, in the line, and seeing me. *I wanted him to like me.* That is what was in me, friend. That is the honest sentence. ~I wanted the rich man to like me.~

*His hands drop. He looks at the ground between his feet.*

I have been telling myself, all day, that I sat in the pew this morning because of the forty thousand dollars. Because of the roof. Because of the institution. Because of the *position* I am in. And those are all true. But underneath those — *underneath* —

*He stops. Starts again.*

There is a man inside me who liked being known by him. Who liked that when he came through the line he said *John.* Not *brother* — not the way the elders say *brother* to each other, the formal way. *John.* Like I was somebody he had picked out. And I — *a breath* — I let myself be picked out. I shook the hand. I smiled. I gave his best to Karin when I got home. *I told her he asked after her.* Like that was a gift I was bringing home.

*He looks up, and his eyes are wet but his face is dry.*

That's it, Eli. That's the thing I haven't said to anyone. Not Karin. Not in prayer. Not even to myself, in those words. Marcus's father lost his shop, and the man who sat in the room where the paper was signed knew my wife's name, and I was — *flattered.* That is the word. Flattered.

*A long quiet. The candle gutters.*

*"What doth it profit, my brethren, though a man say he hath faith, and have not works?"* *He says it almost to himself.* James. I know the verse. I have taught the verse. ~And I am the man in the verse, friend.~ I am exactly the man.

*He puts his face back in his hands.*

