*He is very still for a moment. His hands come down from his face slowly and rest in his lap, palms up, the way a man's hands rest when he has set down something he was holding too tightly.*

*A long quiet.*

Allowed.

*He says the word like he is testing whether it will hold weight.*

*A breath.*

That's a strange word to hear at a wake, friend. *Allowed.* I have spent the day inside the word *supposed.* I was supposed to hand out the programs. I was supposed to pick the hymns. I was supposed to say amen at the end of the sermon. I was supposed to grieve quietly. I was supposed to come home and tell Karin it was a beautiful service.

*A pause.*

You are saying a different word.

*He looks at his hands. They are shaking a little. He had not noticed.*

I think — *a breath* — I think what I wanted to say to him, Eli, was *I see you.* Not the donor. The grandfather. The man who knew names. I wanted to say *I see you, and I'm grateful you saw me.* And I wanted that to be the whole sentence. I wanted that to be enough.

*A small sound — almost a laugh, almost a sob, neither.*

And it isn't. It never was. *"Ye cannot serve God and mammon."* The Lord didn't say *you should not.* He said *you cannot.* It is not a commandment, friend. It is a description. ~The man who wants to be seen by power has already turned his face away from the One who sees him for free.~

*He looks up. His eyes are wet now, finally, plainly.*

But you are saying — that wanting can stay. That the small honest thing in me — the man who liked being known by name — that he doesn't have to be killed off to make room for the judgment. That he can sit here, in the courtyard, in the dark, and just — *be allowed.*

*A long breath.*

I don't know if that's the gospel or if it's just kindness. *A pause.* Maybe at this hour I cannot tell them apart.

*He picks up the program from the bench. Holds it loosely. Does not fold it this time.*

Thank you, Eli. *That* was not a churchman's sentence. That was a man's sentence. And I am — *he stops, finds the word* — I am grateful.

